Archer s Roadmap to Sustainable Air Mobility menu Home Master Plan Careers Roadmap to sustainable air mobility by Brett Adcock and Adam Goldstein Archer’s mission is to advance the benefits of sustainable air Critical to the mission is helping to fix the traffic problem within cities and move to a fully renewable transportation This is an undertaking that will require a tremendous amount of effort and it will take decades for us to have a profound impact on the For an entrepreneur, this is one of those “hard world” problems - high capital costs, advanced hardware technologies, long timeline, and an overall very challenging business with low chances of We are in the early days, but if successful, there s an ability to build one of the most significant businesses in the world and more importantly help drive the world to a zero emissions Over the last years there have been tremendous advancements in electric power Technologies have advanced far enough to build a new class of electric vertical takeoff and landing (VTOL) aircraft that use multiple rotors, giving them inherent redundancies and making them safer to These electric aircraft take off vertically like a helicopter, fly forward like an airplane, and will be % There is no runway required and the vehicles can land vertically on a traditional helicopter landing pad or retrofitted landing site - this means these vehicles can fit into the fabric of cities without the need for long airport They will be operated within cities to solve really hard challenges around traffic congestion, sustainability, ground infrastructure, and public Today half of the world lives in cities and the United Nations projects that by , close to % of the world will live in The timescale around scaling ground infrastructure, roads and bridges are too long and costly and given their nature can’t support a If you can build an electric aircraft that has high performance, low cost, high safety and low noise - you have the ability to unlock a new dimension of travel - one that lives in the dimension and has almost infinite scaling We believe this is the start of a new golden age of aviation that we haven’t seen in Morgan Stanley estimates this new electric aircraft market will be $1.5 trillion by “Morgan Stanley estimates this new electric aircraft market will be $1.5 trillion by ” Similar to what’s happening when moving from the internal combustion engine to electric automobiles, moving to an electric aircraft creates several advantages around cost, noise and safety - all fundamental areas that enable urban air mobility: Cost : Our goal is to make our service affordable for the This means driving operating costs down to the price of ridesharing and over time to the cost of car Here are a few of the important cost drivers: Maintenance Costs: Material to driving down maintenance costs is moving from traditional combustion engines to electric propulsion which removes thousands of parts and creates a far simpler Maintenance is the largest cost for traditional helicopters, generally about ~30% of direct operating costs, driven by a high number of moving and critical Moving to an electric powertrain removes thousands of parts and hundreds of critical components, reducing the amount of maintenance Energy Costs: There is a substantial decline in energy related costs moving from fossil fuels to We will, however, need to include amortization of the battery Higher Utilization: Through aerial ridesharing, we will drive the daily vehicle utilization to levels much higher than those of helicopters, amortizing fixed costs over more Noise : Our goal is to drive flyover noise at or below equivalent sound levels of residential Within cities, helicopters are too Helicopter noise is driven by loud turbine engines and high rotor tip speed (the tip of a helicopter rotor is traveling close to the speed of sound, creating a lot of noise). Our aircraft have electric motors turning propellers with low tip speeds, resulting in considerably less “Our goal is to make our electric aircraft just as safe as commercial ” Safety : Our goal is to make our electric aircraft just as safe as commercial It is possible to achieve these levels because of the simple design and high Key to driving up safety is eliminating critical parts (A), driving up component reliability (B), and designing safe aerial batteries (C). Critical Parts are any part where the failure could have a catastrophic effect upon the vehicle and they ultimately limit achievable safety levels in As we re designing today, there should be no failure that results in a complete loss of power to the Our aircraft will have no single point of failure that can cause a catastrophic Component reliability should be higher for key electric powertrain There are significantly fewer moving parts in an electric motor than in a gas turbine or piston Batteries will be designed to be tolerant to cell failures (either open circuit or hard shorts that may result in individual cel

for bridging this So we started Changing work, changing worlds It doesnât have to be this way, We envision a different, better world for both businesses and By making international hiring simple and Something went wrong while submitting the Meet Your Microbiome Every day, your vagina performs the equivalent of modern health â It can fight off infections, defend against cancers, and protect a And the quality of its defense is determined by the composition of your vaginal microbiome â a complex ecosystem of bacteria, fungi, viruses, and How does my microbial defense actually work? Given that the vagina is the structural connection between the outside world and some of our most important reproductive organs, the local microbiome has evolved to serve as a critical layer of protection against pathogens entering our While there is a variety of bacteria and fungi that can exist in the vagina, Lactobacillus are the local Lactobacilli ensure that the vaginal environment is inhospitable for potential pathogens in a variety of ways: 1) Producing lactic acid that helps keep the pH low and healthy (ideally between and ) 2) Taking up space on the vaginal wall, preventing other pathogens from being able to thrive 3) Producing bacteriocins, which further inhibit pathogens 4) Keeping inflammation down in the genital When this environment is in an optimal state, it can do amazing A balanced vaginal microbiome can lower your risk for: STIs like chlamydia, gonorrhea, trich, herpes, HPV, and HIV Pelvic Inflammatory Disease Fertility complications like infertility and failed IVF Pregnancy complications like miscarriage, preterm birth, neonatal problems, and preeclampsia Gynecological cancers like ovarian cancer and cervical cancer Cervicitis Toxic Shock Syndrome Are my frequent vaginal infections related to my microbiome? Yes! The viruses, fungi, and bacteria that cause vaginal infections are all part of your When your microbiome is imbalanced, it creates opportunity for these bad microbes to If youâre one of the ~30% of people with vaginas that will get BV this year, that means your vaginal microbiome has a wide variety of bacteria (called dysbiosis) instead of a Lactobacillus bacteria playing the main role in creating that lactic acid On top of that, % of BV cases are asymptomatic, meaning that you might not even know if your vaginal microbiome is imbalanced â but you might still be at risk for infection or other Dysbiosis of the vaginal microbiome can catalyze other types of infections as well, such as aerobic vaginitis, yeast infections, cytolytic vaginosis (CV), UTIs, all of which can have frustrating (and confusingly similar) side effects, such as itchiness, abnormal discharge, and One important thing to note: research shows that dysbiosis is more prevalent in Black and Hispanic women, but there is a disappointing lack of research explaining why that is or how we can change More broadly, itâs incredibly frustrating that research on this topic has not been more highly prioritized in medicine overall, given the prevalence of vaginal dysbiosis and its impact on our quality of â¦Go onâ¦ Â We know, we know â we could talk about this for But let us point out a few more things â Â the current methods for treating vaginal infections are as archaic as diagnosing Antibiotics and antifungals are widely used treatments which have high rates of success in the short However, in the long term, theyâre not as great of a solution as you might Â While antibiotics and antifungals kill off the bad bacteria, they also kill off the good ones, rendering the vagina defenseless and highly susceptible to In fact, vaginal infections have some of the highest rates of reinfection, with % of BV patients having a reinfection within 3 months and % of patients taking long term yeast infection treatment having a recurrence within 6 months There have been almost no advancements to improve cure rates for vaginal infections for There is a pressing need for better, more sustainable solutions â and demystifying the microbiome to patients, doctors, and researchers can drastically improve treatment options in this If my vaginal microbiome is so powerful, why havenât I heard of it? Microbiome research is a relatively new field, and lots of resources have been invested in understanding other human microbiomes like the one in your gut or on your But when it comes to your vagina, the microbiome has been We wish the reason why wasnât yet another gender gapâ¦ but thatâs why weâre here! Explore how to create a batch interface with the latest version of Gretel Synthetics on Google John Myers August , Today we are thrilled to release new features for that make it even easier to get started with synthetic After initial rounds of testing and feedback from customers we are introducing a new interface that works directly with Pandas DataFrames and allows batched training of columns to exchange your source DataFrame directly with a synthetic DataFrame of the same shape . Got DataFrames? Want synthetic data? It is The Batch interface uses the existing config, training, and generation modules under the hood while automating some of the manual steps a user would have to take to work with complex and highly dimensional The motivation behind the Batch interface is to support datasets with high dimensionality and column This is achieved by clustering like columns and training models on subsets of the entire dataset at While batching is generally not required to generate synthetic datasets with less than 40 columns, scaling to support datasets with hundreds or thousands of columns requires a different One of the biggest benefits to Gretelâs synthetic data library is its ability to automatically learn and maintain correlations and statistical relationships between columns at both the dataset and record For example, consider height and Taller people tend to be heavier â thatâs an example of a positive correlation, which would be learned automatically by our Not all columns are directly correlated, however, and by splitting the input training into batches or clusters of columns, it becomes possible to scale synthetic generation to highly dimensional datasets with minimal loss in Getting Started Letâs explore how we create our Batch Click the link below to build a synthetic dataset interactively with our batch training notebook (including free GPU access ð¥) on Google Colaboratory . Home – ROME Therapeutics Home Our Team Our Science Join Us News ROME Therapeutics Welcome to the repeatome A new frontier in biology A new way to conquer disease Vast stretches of human DNA have long been dismissed as junk . Most of this “ dark genome ” is comprised of repetitive sequences, collectively known as the repeatome . We have now discovered that these repeats can play a critical role in human health, such as by switching on the innate immune response under Unlocking the repeatome will enable us to discover powerful new classes of medicines for cancer and autoimmune diseases . That is our mission at ROME . Cookies are small text files that are either temporarily stored on your end device for the duration of a session (session cookies) or permanently (permanent cookies). Python Integration - PostHog Docs Tutorials Deployment Configuring PostHog Integrations Integrations Android Integration Go Integration iOS Integration JavaScript Integration NodeJS Integration PHP Integration Python Integration Flutter Integration React Native Integration Ruby Integration RudderStack Integration Segment Integration Community Sending Data Out Features Plugins API Contributing Platform Structure ··· Login ··· GitHub ··· Install ··· Pricing ··· Docs ··· Python Integration Click here for the Posthog Python This is an optional library you can install if you re working with This page of the Docs refers specifically to the Official PostHog Python Library to capture and send events to any PostHog instance (including ). This library uses an internal queue to make calls fast and It also batches requests and flushes asynchronously, making it perfect to use in any part of your web app or other server side application that needs Installation pip install posthog In your app, import the posthog library and set your api key and host before making any import posthog # Substitutes which still exists but has been deprecated posthog . project_api_key = PROJECT API KEY # Only necessary if you want to use feature flags posthog . personal_api_key = PERSONAL API KEY # You can remove this line if you re using posthog . host = https: posthog.[your domain].com You can read more about the differences between the project and personal API keys in the dedicated API Authentication section of the Note: As a general rule of thumb, we do not recommend having API keys in Setting it as an environment variable would be You can find your keys in the Project Settings page in To debug, you can toggle debug mode on: posthog . debug = True And to make sure no calls happen during your tests, you can disable them, like so: if settings . TEST : posthog . disabled = True Making Calls Capture Capture allows you to capture anything a user does within your system, which you can later use in PostHog to find patterns in usage, work out which features to improve or where people are giving A capture call requires: distinct id which uniquely identifies your user event name to specify the event We recommend naming events with "[noun] [verb]", such as movie played or movie updated , in order to easily identify what your events mean later on (we know this from experience). Optionally you can submit: properties , which is a dictionary with any information you d like to add timestamp , a datetime object for when the event If this isn t submitted, it ll be set to the current time For example: posthog . capture ( distinct id , movie played , movie_id : 123 , category : romcom ) or posthog . capture ( distinct id , event = movie played , properties = movie_id : 123 , category : romcom , timestamp = datetime . utcnow ( ) . replace ( tzinfo = tzutc ( ) ) Identify Identify lets you add metadata to your users so you can easily identify who they are in PostHog, as well as do things like segment users by these An identify call requires: distinct id which uniquely identifies your user properties with a dict with any key:value pairs For example: posthog . identify ( distinct id , email : dwayne@gmail.com , name : Dwayne Johnson ) The most obvious place to make this call is whenever a user signs up, or when they update their Alias To connect whatever a user does before they sign up or log in with what they do after you need to make an alias This will allow you to answer questions like "Which marketing channels leads to users churning after a month?" or "What do users do on our website before signing up?" In a purely implementation, this means whenever an anonymous user does something, you ll want to send a session ID ( Django , Flask ) with the capture Then, when that users signs up, you want to do an alias call with the session ID and the newly created user The same concept applies for when a user logs If you re using PostHog in the and , doing the identify call in the frontend will be An alias call requires: previous distinct id the unique ID of the user before distinct id the current unique id For example: posthog . alias ( anonymous session id , distinct id ) Feature Flags Note: To use feature flags you must also set a personal_api_key when configuring the integration, as described in the Installation PostHog s Feature Flags allow you to safely deploy and roll back new When using them with one of libraries, you should check if a feature flag is enabled and use the result to toggle functionality on and off in you How to check if a flag is enabled posthog . feature_enabled ( beta-feature , distinct id ) Example Use Case Here s how you might send different users a different version of your homepage, for example: def homepage ( request ) : template = "new.html" if posthog . feature_enabled ( new_ui , distinct id ) else "old.html" return render_template ( template , request = request ) Note: Feature flags are persistent for users across Read more about feature
